04176nam a22005775i 9780822395225DE-B159720201028084219.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201028t20122012ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223952257 a10.1515/97808223952252doi  a(DE-B1597)552333  a(OCoLC)779617234  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPN1993.5.I8 7aPER0040302bisacsh04a791.4309547921 aGanti, Tejaswini, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aProducing Bollywood :bInside the Contemporary Hindi Film Industry /cTejaswini Ganti. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource (440 p.) :b28 photographs, 6 tables, 2 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: How the Hindi Film Industry Became "Bollywood" -- t1. From Vice to Virtue -- t2. From Slumdogs to Millionaires -- t3. Casting Respectability -- t4. A Day in the Life of a Hindi Film Set -- t5. The Structure, Organization, and Social Relations of the Hindi Film Industry -- t6. Sentiments of Disdain and Practices of Distinction -- t7. Risky Business -- t8. Pleasing Both Aunties and Servants -- t9. The Fear of Large Numbers -- tEpilogue My Name Is Bollywood -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aProducing Bollywood offers an unprecedented look inside the social and professional worlds of the Mumbai-based Hindi film industry and explains how it became "Bollywood," the global film phenomenon and potent symbol of India as a rising economic powerhouse. In this rich and entertaining ethnography Tejaswini Ganti examines the changes in Hindi film production from the 1990s until 2010, locating them in Hindi filmmakers' efforts to accrue symbolic capital, social respectability, and professional distinction, and to manage the commercial uncertainties of filmmaking. These efforts have been enabled by the neoliberal restructuring of the Indian state and economy since 1991. This restructuring has dramatically altered the country's media landscape, which quickly expanded to include satellite television and multiplex theaters. Ganti contends that the Hindi film industry's metamorphosis into Bollywood would not have been possible without the rise of neoliberal economic ideals in India. By describing dramatic transformations in the Hindi film industry's production culture, daily practices, and filmmaking ideologies during a decade of tremendous social and economic change in India, Ganti offers valuable new insights into the effects of neoliberalism on cultural production in a postcolonial setting.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aIncludes index. 0aMotion picture industryzIndiazBombay. 0aMotion picture industryzIndia. 0aMotion pictures, HindizIndiazBombay. 0aMotion pictures, HindizIndia. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822395225zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822395225423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822395225.jpg  a978-3-11-071183-7  DUK Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles